text:
A second shipment of food, 
water and medical supplies
has crossed the border from Egypt into Gaza.

And Australia's prime minister is 
planning to travel to Beijing next month.

Good morning. I'm Korva Coleman, from NPR 
News, and here are today's top stories:

The Israel Defense Forces say they conducted well 
over 300 strikes on targets in Gaza overnight

as the war between Israel and Hamas continues. 
Israel says Hamas killed 1,400 people — mostly

Israelis — when the militants attacked two 
weeks ago. Palestinian health authoritities

now say at least 4,600 Palestinians have 
been killed in Israeli air strikes in Gaza.

A second shipment of humanitarian aid 
has arrived in Gaza. NPR's Jackie Northam

reports from Jerusalem it was limited to 
14 trucks with water, food and medicine:

The second convoy of aid trucks passed 
through the Rafa Crossing after a long

delay. Each truck was thoroughly inspected to 
make sure no weapons bound for Hamas militants

were on board. Relief workers say the supplies 
are just a fraction of what's needed for the

more than 700,000 Palestinians who have fled 
their homes in Northern Gaza to escape constant

air strikes by the Israeli military. On Sunday, 
President Biden spoke with Israeli Prime Minister

Benjamin Netanyahu and affirmed there would be 
a continued flow of humanitarian aid into Gaza.

That could change if and when an anticipated 
Israeli incursion into Gaza gets underway.
Jackie Northam, NPR News, Jerusalem.

Republican congressman George Santos 
will be a key vote this week as the

GOP struggles to elect a new House Speaker. 
But the scandal-plagued congressman from New

York is also expected back in federal court 
on Long Island. NPR's Brian Mann explains:

George Santos posted on social media that 
he expects to receive the longest Speaker

ballot in modern history this week, describing 
it as a historic mark for the 118th Congress.

Candidates for the speakership have so far 
failed to receive the 217 votes needed to

lead the narrowly divided House, and Santos' vote 
could be crucial, but if the process drags on,

Santos is also scheduled back in 
federal court on Long Island Friday,

facing new felony corruption counts. Federal 
prosecutors say Santos tried to rack up big,

unauthorized charges on the credit cards of his 
political donors. Santos has admitted lying to

voters about much of his life's story, but denies 
any criminal wrongdoing. Earlier this month,

his campaign treasurer pleaded guilty to 
charges linked to her work on his campaign.
Brian Mann, NPR News.

Australia's Prime Minister, Anthony Albanese, says 
he will travel to Beijing next month. NPR's Emily

Fang says he'll be the first Australian 
leader to visit China in seven years:

Tensions with China escalated after Australia's 
then-Prime Minister Scott Morrison called for

an independent investigation into the origins of 
COVID in China in 2020, but since being elected to

power last year, Albanese's government has sought 
to ease tensions with Beijing. He'll attend a

big export fair in China next month. China's 
release of an Australian political prisoner,

the journalist Cheng Lei, this month, 
also marked a diplomatic breakthrough.
NPR's Emily Fang.
This is NPR.
